@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{calendar-extras.el} extends Emacs' built-in @code{calendar} library with
geolocation awareness, date utilities, and visual agenda display.  The
package exists because the stock calendar has no facility for
automatically determining the user's location, and common date
arithmetic tasks---such as finding the last day of the previous month
or enumerating every date in a range---require boilerplate that is
better factored into reusable helpers.

The geolocation subsystem (@ref{Geolocation}) fetches latitude, longitude,
and city name from an IP-based service and stores them for use by
sunrise/sunset calculations and other location-dependent features.

The date utilities (@ref{Date utilities}) cover inserting formatted dates and
generating date ranges.  A separate command (@ref{Block agenda}) displays
the current day's Org agenda in the @samp{calfw} visual time-block view.

@node User options
@chapter User options

@menu
* Geolocation settings::
@end menu

@node Geolocation settings
@section Geolocation settings

@vindex calendar-extras-location-name
The user option @code{calendar-extras-location-name} stores the name of the
current location as a string.  You can set it manually, or let
@code{calendar-extras-set-geolocation} populate it automatically from an IP
lookup (@ref{Geolocation}).  The default value is an empty string.

@vindex calendar-extras-personal-geolocation
The user option @code{calendar-extras-personal-geolocation} holds an alist
of geolocation data.  Each key is a city name (a string) and each
value is a plist with @samp{:latitude} (float), @samp{:longitude} (float), and
@samp{:timezone} (string).  Like @code{calendar-extras-location-name}, this
option is typically set by @code{calendar-extras-set-geolocation} rather
than by hand.  The default value is an empty list.

@vindex calendar-extras-use-geolocation
The user option @code{calendar-extras-use-geolocation} is a boolean that
controls whether geolocation features are active.  When non-nil,
@code{calendar-extras-set-geolocation} can automatically determine and set
location-related variables.  The default value is @code{nil}.

