@node Geolocation
@section Geolocation

@findex calendar-extras-set-geolocation
When you move to a different city and want calendar computations
(sunrise/sunset, holidays) to reflect your new location, invoke
@code{calendar-extras-set-geolocation}.  The command calls the Geoapify
API---using an API key retrieved from @samp{auth-source-pass} under the
entry @samp{tlon/core/api.geoapify.com}---to look up your latitude,
longitude, and city name from your IP address.  It then writes the
result into @code{calendar-extras-personal-geolocation} and
@code{calendar-extras-location-name} and confirms the update in the echo
area.

Internally, the command delegates the HTTP request to
@code{calendar-extras-get-geolocation} (@ref{Fetching geolocation data}).

@node Date utilities
@section Date utilities

@findex calendar-extras-time-last-day-of-last-month
Bookkeeping and reporting tasks often need the last day of the
previous month.  The command @code{calendar-extras-time-last-day-of-last-month}
computes that date and inserts it at point in @samp{YYYY-MM-DD} format.  It
handles the January boundary correctly, rolling back to December of
the previous year when necessary.

@node Block agenda
@section Block agenda

@findex calendar-extras-calfw-block-agenda
If you use the @samp{calfw} (Calendar Framework) package and prefer a
visual, time-blocked view of your day, the command
@code{calendar-extras-calfw-block-agenda} opens a @samp{calfw} buffer in
@samp{block-day} view, sourcing its contents from Org agenda items.  This
provides an at-a-glance alternative to the standard Org agenda
dispatcher.

